property.name: commonFeedback
property.value:
The not-a-knot fit can be set up with the following script:

 

x = [0 100 200 400 600 800 1000]; y = x/200.*exp(-x/200+1);
xx = linspace(0,1000);
yc = xx/200.*exp(-xx/200+1);
yy = spline(x,y,xx);
plot(x,y,'o',xx,yy,xx,yc,'--')

 

%media:18.004.b.jpg%

 

The piecewise cubic Hermite polynomial fit can be set up with the following script:

 

x = [0 100 200 400 600 800 1000]; y = x/200.*exp(-x/200+1);
xx = linspace(0,1000);
yc = xx/200.*exp(-xx/200+1);
yy = interp1(x,y,xx,'pchip');
plot(x,y,'o',xx,yy,xx,yc,'--')

 

%media:18.004.jpg%

 

Comparing the cubic spline fit of the data with natural end conditions, not-a-knot end conditions, and piecewise cubic Hermite interpolation fit, the not-a-knot end fit seems to be the best.

worksheet.stem:
Find the value of J1 (2.1) using cubic splines. Note that true value is 0.5683. (Round the final answer to five decimal places.)

 

The value of  J1 (2.1) = __a__
worksheet.commonFeedback:
A program can be developed to fit natural cubic splines through data based on M-file for natspline that uses natural cubic spline. If this program runs with the data of this problem, the interpolation at 2.1 is 0.56846 that has a relative error of εt = 0.0295%.

 

A spline can also be fit with MATLAB. It should be noted that MATLAB does not use a natural spline. Rather, it uses a “not-a-knot” spline. Thus, as given below, although it also yields a very good prediction, the result differs from the one generated with the natural spline.

 

>> format long
>> x=[1.8 2 2.2 2.4 2.6]; y=[0.5815 0.5767 0.556 0.5202 0.4708];
>> spline(x,y,2.1)

ans =
    0.56829843750000

 

This result has a relative error of  εt = 0.00035%.

worksheet.stem:
Use MATLAB to fit the data with piecewise linear interpolation and estimate o(27). Note that the exact result is 7.986 mg/L. (Round the final answer to three decimal places.)

 

The value of o(27) = __a__ mg/L.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
The script generates the solution is as follows:

 

>> otrue=7.986;
>> % piecewise linear interpolation:
>> T=[0 8 16 24 32 40];
>> o=[14.621 11.843 9.870 8.418 7.305 6.413];
>> opred=interp1(T,o,27);
>> et=abs((otrue-opred)/otrue)*100;
>> fprintf('o(27)-linear = %8.4g et = %8.4g pct\n', opred,et)

 

Output

 

o(27)-linear = 8.001 et = 0.1831 pct

Here is a MATLAB script to develop the spline and plot it along with the data:

 

>> x=[0 2 4 7 10 12]; y=[20 20 12 7 6 6];
>> xx=linspace(0,12);
>> yy=spline(x,y,xx);
>> plot(x,y,'o',xx,yy)

worksheet.stem:
Use MATLAB to fit a cubic spline to the given data to determine y at x = 1.5 with zero first derivatives at the end knots. (Round the final answer to four decimal places.)

 

The value of y is __a__.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
To prescribe zero first derivatives at the end knots, the y vector is modified so that the first and last elements are set to the desired values of zero. The plot and the prediction both indicate that there is less overshoot between the first two points because of the prescribed zero slopes.

 

>> x=[0 2 4 7 10 12]; y=[20 20 12 7 6 6];
>> xx=linspace(0,12);
>> yd=[0 y 0];
>> yy=spline(x,yd,xx);
>> plot(x,y,'o',xx,yy)
>> yy=spline(x,yd,1.5)

yy =
   20.5701

sectionBreak.stem:
The following function describes the temperature distribution on a rectangular plate for the range −2 ≤ x ≤ 0 and 0 ≤ y ≤ 3.

 

%media:formula13.mml%

internal_category.title: ABET Outcomes: (a) an ability to apply knowledge of mathematics, science, and engineering

property.name: problemSolution
property.value:
The value of the temperature using interp2 function is 1.4626 °C.

The percent relative error of the result is 4.4786%.

hint.name: hint #1
hint.value: What are the arguments required for the interp2 function?

worksheet.stem:
Use the MATLAB function interp2 with the default interpolation option ('linear') to compute the temperature at x = –1.63 and y = 1.627. Determine the percent relative error of the result. Note: employ the linspace function with nine interior points and generate a meshgrid. (Round the final answers to four decimal places.)

 

The value of the temperature using interp2 function is __a__°C.

 

The percent relative error of the result is __b__%.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
The MATLAB code is as follows:

 

>> clear,clc,format short g
>> x=linspace(-2,0,9);y=linspace(0,3,9);
>> [X,Y] = meshgrid(x,y);
>> Z=2+X-Y+2*X.^2+2*X.*Y+Y.^2;
>> xunk=-1.63;yunk=1.627;
>> ztrue=2+xunk-yunk+2*xunk.^2+2*xunk.*yunk+yunk.^2
>> zlinear=interp2(X,Y,Z,xunk,yunk)
>> et=abs((ztrue-zlinear)/ztrue)*100

 

Result:

 

ztrue =
      1.3999


zlinear =
        1.4626


et =
   4.4786

internal_category.title: ABET Outcomes: (a) an ability to apply knowledge of mathematics, science, and engineering
